article.headline: Phoenix gets first victory of season
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Diana Taurasi was all business in her
return to Connecticut.

The former UConn star scored 26 points to lead Phoenix to a
65-58 win Saturday over the Connecticut Sun in her second pro game
and first in the state where she led the Huskies to three straight
NCAA titles.

To Connecticut fans, it was all so familiar with Taurasi hitting
from long range, finding a teammate with a no-look pass and
draining a smooth fadeaway.

Only this time, she was on the other side, wearing the bright
orange colors of the Phoenix Mercury. Still, it was clear who was
No. 1 with the crowd.

"There is no better state than Connecticut for basketball,"
Taurasi said. "The crowds they get, people love the game. It's
like you're family."

Taurasi drew a standing ovation during introductions from the
sellout crowd of 9,341. Dozens of fans wore her familiar UConn
jersey and there were countless signs welcoming her back. She drew
cheers each time she scored en route to spoiling the Sun's season
opener.

Sitting just three rows behind the Sun bench, fan Andrea Murphy,
20, of nearby Norwich, proudly wore her Taurasi UConn jersey at the
same time rooting for the home team.

"I hope that Phoenix loses but that Diana has a 20-something
points," Murphy said. "We want to see her have a great game."

She got half her wish.

It was the first win for Phoenix (1-1), which selected Taurasi
with the first pick in the WNBA draft last month. Anna DeForge
added 17 points and had six assists for the Mercury. DeForge and
Penny Taylor controlled the boards with seven rebounds each.

"Diana felt right at home here," Phoenix coach Carrie Graf
said. "She made some huge shots and got her teammates involved.
She's a special person."

Taj McWilliams-Franklin led Connecticut with 14 points. Wendy
Palmer scored 10 points and had a team-high 10 boards for the Sun.

The game also marked the debut of Sun rookie Lindsay Whalen, who
led Minnesota to the Final Four in March. She struggled early
before getting all five of her points in the final two minutes of
the game.

"We'll figure it out," Whalen said. "We've just got to
fight."

Whalen and Taurasi often guarded each other and the rookie vs.
rookie matchup made for an interesting side show. Whalen was called
for a block on Taurasi in the lane that sent the Phoenix rookie
crashing hard to her knees. She was slow getting up.

Other moments were more amiable. Taurasi could be heard asking
Whalen how she liked Connecticut and playing for Sun, whose home
games are in a casino. Whalen replied that she was enjoying
herself.

"Yeah, but you can't gamble," Taurasi quipped.

Sun players are prohibited from gambling in Mohegan Sun casino.

The Sun rushed several shots and missed 17 layups. Coach Mike
Thibault said defensively the team was supposed to make Taurasi
dribble and contest her 3s.

"Yet we let her shoot jump shots," he said. "We switched when
we shouldn't have switched. They got 68 percent of their points
from Taurasi and DeForge. It's not a good thing."

Taurasi had trouble early offensively, missing her first five
shots in a choppy first half for both teams. She heated up in the
closing minutes of the period and made it look easy the rest of the
way, finishing 5-of-7 from 3-point range.

"I didn't want to go out there and make it seem like I was
trying to force stuff," Taurasi said. "As a team I think we
played a little tentative for the first 12 to 14 minutes. Towards
the end we picked it up."

Her 3-pointer with 2:27 remaining put the Mercury up for good at
21-18. She scored the final eight points of the half to give
Phoenix a 26-22 lead at the break.

She scored 11 points in an 18-2 Phoenix run midway through the
second half on a pair of 3s, a fadeway jumper and a three-point
play as the Mercury built a 57-36 lead.

Taurasi shot 8-for-15 from the field with four assists, two
steals and a blocked shot.

Several of her former college teammates were in attendance and
her former coach Geno Auriemma served as TV analyst for the game.
From his courtside seat, it all looked familiar to him, too.

"There's just so many things she does so well that I can see
her doing this on a regular basis," Auriemma said.
